      <p class="key-stat-txt">of American adults do not meet the Recommended Dietary Allowance of 15mg vitamin E per day from food alone, according to USDA dietary intake data. This makes vitamin E one of the most under-consumed essential nutrients in the Western diet — a gap that moderate supplementation can close safely.</p>
    </div>

    <p>Despite its critical role in cellular protection, vitamin E is remarkably difficult to obtain from diet alone. The richest sources — wheat germ oil, sunflower seeds, almonds — are not staples in most American diets. A 2019 analysis of NHANES data found that the average American adult consumes only 7.2mg of alpha-tocopherol daily — less than half the 15mg RDA. This chronic insufficiency does not cause overt deficiency symptoms in most people, but it may contribute to suboptimal antioxidant defense, accelerated skin aging, and reduced immune resilience over time.</p>

