      <cite>JAMA, 2004 — 617 participants, randomized controlled trial</cite>
    </div>

    <h3>Natural vs. Synthetic Vitamin E: A Difference That Actually Matters</h3>

    <p>Unlike many supplement ingredients where natural and synthetic forms are equivalent, vitamin E is a case where the source genuinely matters for bioavailability. Natural vitamin E (d-alpha-tocopherol) is a single stereoisomer that the body's alpha-tocopherol transfer protein preferentially binds, transports, and retains. Synthetic vitamin E (dl-alpha-tocopherol) is a mixture of eight stereoisomers, only one of which is the natural RRR form. The result: natural vitamin E is approximately twice as bioavailable as synthetic. Our top picks all use natural-source d-alpha-tocopherol.</p>

    <div class="tip-box">
      <span class="tip-box-ico">&#128161;</span>
      <p><strong>Label reading tip:</strong> The "d-" prefix means natural vitamin E (e.g., d-alpha-tocopherol, d-alpha-tocopheryl acetate). The "dl-" prefix means synthetic (e.g., dl-alpha-tocopherol). Natural forms provide roughly 1.5x the biological activity per milligram. Also note that vitamin E doses are now expressed in mg rather than IU: 1mg natural vitamin E = 1.49 IU; 1mg synthetic = 1.10 IU.</p>
    </div>

