      <h3>Vitamin E: What the Science Says</h3>
      <p>Vitamin E is among the most extensively researched antioxidant nutrients, with clinical evidence spanning skin protection, immune function, and cellular defense.</p>

      <div class="vs-strip">
        <div class="vs-item">
          <strong>Immune Enhancement in Elderly</strong>
          <p>Vitamin E at 200 IU/day reduced upper respiratory infections by 20% in adults over 65 in a randomized controlled trial of 617 nursing home residents.<br /><em>JAMA, 2004</em></p>
        </div>
        <div class="vs-item">
          <strong>Skin Photoprotection</strong>
          <p>Vitamin E supplementation improved skin hydration, reduced UV-induced erythema, and supported wound healing in a review of clinical evidence.<br /><em>Indian Dermatology Online Journal, 2016</em></p>
        </div>
        <div class="vs-item">
          <strong>Natural vs. Synthetic Bioavailability</strong>
          <p>Natural d-alpha-tocopherol is approximately twice as bioavailable as synthetic dl-alpha-tocopherol due to preferential binding by the liver's alpha-tocopherol transfer protein.<br /><em>Am J Clinical Nutrition, 2012</em></p>
        </div>
        <div class="vs-item">
          <strong>Mixed Tocopherols Advantage</strong>
          <p>Gamma-tocopherol demonstrated superior neutralization of reactive nitrogen species compared to alpha-tocopherol alone, suggesting broader antioxidant protection from mixed forms.<br /><em>Free Radical Biology and Medicine, 2014</em></p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

