    <!-- FAQ SECTION -->
    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions About Vitamin E Gummies</h2>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What does vitamin E do for the body?</summary>
      <p>Vitamin E is a fat-soluble antioxidant that protects cell membranes from free radical damage. It supports immune function, skin health, cardiovascular health, and neurological protection. It is the primary lipid-phase antioxidant in human tissues.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What is the difference between natural and synthetic vitamin E?</summary>
      <p>Natural vitamin E (d-alpha-tocopherol) is approximately twice as bioavailable as synthetic (dl-alpha-tocopherol). Look for the "d-" prefix on labels for the natural form. The body preferentially binds and retains the natural stereoisomer.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>How much vitamin E should I take daily?</summary>
      <p>The RDA is 15mg (22.4 IU) for adults. The UL is 1,000mg (1,500 IU natural). Over 90% of Americans do not meet the RDA from food alone, making moderate supplementation (100-400 IU) reasonable for most adults.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Is vitamin E good for skin?</summary>
      <p>Yes. Vitamin E integrates into the skin lipid barrier, neutralizing free radicals from UV and pollution. It improves hydration, reduces erythema, and supports wound healing. It works synergistically with vitamin C for enhanced protection.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Should I take vitamin E with food?</summary>
      <p>Yes. Vitamin E is fat-soluble and absorption increases by up to 330% when taken with a fat-containing meal. Gummies contain some oil that partially enhances absorption, but taking them with food optimizes uptake.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Can vitamin E interact with medications?</summary>
      <p>Yes. Vitamin E has mild anticoagulant properties and can interact with blood thinners (warfarin, heparin, aspirin). High-dose vitamin E exceeding 400 IU may increase bleeding risk. Discontinue high-dose supplements two weeks before surgery.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What are the best food sources of vitamin E?</summary>
      <p>Top sources include wheat germ oil, sunflower seeds, almonds, hazelnuts, peanut butter, spinach, and avocado. Despite these available sources, over 90% of Americans do not meet the RDA through diet alone.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What are mixed tocopherols and are they better?</summary>
      <p>Mixed tocopherols include all four natural forms (alpha, beta, gamma, delta). Gamma-tocopherol has unique anti-inflammatory properties. Mixed tocopherols more closely mimic the vitamin E found in whole foods and may provide broader antioxidant protection.</p>
    </details>

